---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="To Correct, or Stay Silent — A Herbert Spencer Decision Tree"
  description="Herbert Spencer's 1879 framework for when to call out a wrong statement and when to let it pass, presented as a decision tree and a flowchart."
>
  <Fragment slot="utility-right">
    <span>Negative Beneficence</span>
    <span>Herbert Spencer, 1879</span>
  </Fragment>

  <header class="hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="eyebrow">A Decision Tree</div>
      <h1>To Correct,<br />or Stay Silent</h1>
      <p class="sub">
        Someone says something you believe to be wrong. Do you speak up or let it slide?
        Herbert Spencer worked through this dilemma in <em>The Data of Ethics</em>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="source">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="label">The Original Text</div>
      <blockquote>
        "Over the dinner table, or in groups of persons otherwise held together, there
        frequently occur cases in which an erroneous statement is made or an invalid argument
        urged. One who recognizes the error may either display his superior knowledge or
        superior logic, or he may let the error pass in silence: not wishing to raise the
        estimate of himself at the cost of lowering the estimate of another. Which shall he
        do? A proper decision implies several considerations. Is the wrong statement or
        invalid argument one which will do appreciable mischief if it passes uncorrected? Is
        the person who utters it vain, or one whose self-esteem is excessive? Is he
        improperly regarded as an authority by those around? Does he trample down others in
        the pursuit of applause? If to some or all of these questions the answer is — Yes,
        the correction may fitly be made; alike for the benefit of the individual himself
        and for the benefit of hearers. But should the error be trivial, or should the
        credit of one who makes it, not higher than is proper, be unduly injured by the
        exposure, or should his general behavior in social intercourse be of a praiseworthy
        kind, then sympathy may fitly dictate silence — negative beneficence may rightly
        restrain the natural desire to show superiority."
      </blockquote>
      <cite>— Herbert Spencer, <em>The Data of Ethics</em> (1879)</cite>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="tree">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="tree-intro">Work Through It</div>
      <p>
        Start at the top. Each "Yes" pushes you toward correcting. Reach the bottom with
        mostly "No" and silence is the kinder, smarter call.
      </p>

      <div class="node">
        <div class="q">
          <div class="step">Question 01 — Stakes</div>
          <h3>Will the error actually cause harm if it goes uncorrected?</h3>
          <p class="plain">
            Does this matter? If the false claim could mislead people, spread, or do real
            damage, it's worth addressing. If it's harmless trivia, the stakes are low.
          </p>
          <p class="original">
            "Is the wrong statement or invalid argument one which will do appreciable
            mischief if it passes uncorrected?"
          </p>
          <div class="branches">
            <span class="pill yes">Yes <small>lean toward correcting</small></span>
            <span class="pill no">No <small>lean toward silence</small></span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="connector">Then ask</div>

      <div class="node">
        <div class="q">
          <div class="step">Question 02 — Ego</div>
          <h3>Is this person arrogant or overly full of themselves?</h3>
          <p class="plain">
            Are they speaking from genuine confidence, or inflated self-regard? Correcting a
            humble person costs them dignity. Correcting an arrogant one mostly costs them
            air.
          </p>
          <p class="original">
            "Is the person who utters it vain, or one whose self-esteem is excessive?"
          </p>
          <div class="branches">
            <span class="pill yes">Yes <small>lean toward correcting</small></span>
            <span class="pill no">No <small>lean toward silence</small></span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="connector">Then ask</div>

      <div class="node">
        <div class="q">
          <div class="step">Question 03 — Authority</div>
          <h3>Are people wrongly treating them as an expert?</h3>
          <p class="plain">
            If others defer to this person as a trusted voice, their error carries further
            than it should. An unearned platform raises the cost of letting it slide.
          </p>
          <p class="original">"Is he improperly regarded as an authority by those around?"</p>
          <div class="branches">
            <span class="pill yes">Yes <small>lean toward correcting</small></span>
            <span class="pill no">No <small>lean toward silence</small></span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="connector">Then ask</div>

      <div class="node">
        <div class="q">
          <div class="step">Question 04 — Conduct</div>
          <h3>Do they bulldoze other people to win attention?</h3>
          <p class="plain">
            Is this someone who talks over others and grabs applause at their expense? If
            so, a correction restores some balance. If they're decent and generous in
            conversation, that weighs toward leaving them be.
          </p>
          <p class="original">"Does he trample down others in the pursuit of applause?"</p>
          <div class="branches">
            <span class="pill yes">Yes <small>lean toward correcting</small></span>
            <span class="pill no">No <small>lean toward silence</small></span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="outcomes">
        <div class="outcome correct">
          <div class="tag">If mostly YES</div>
          <h4>Correct It</h4>
          <p>
            The error is consequential, the speaker can absorb it, and people are listening.
            Speaking up serves both the person and the room. Make the correction.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="outcome silent">
          <div class="tag">If mostly NO</div>
          <h4>Stay Silent</h4>
          <p>
            The error is trivial, the speaker is decent, and no real harm follows. Let it
            pass. Spencer calls this <em>negative beneficence</em> — kindness through
            restraint.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="social">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>Main Points</h2>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="n">01</div>
        <div class="t">
          <strong>"Being right isn't a reason to say it."</strong>
          <span>
            The question isn't whether you <em>can</em> correct someone. It's whether the
            correction does more good than the embarrassment does harm.
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="n">02</div>
        <div class="t">
          <strong>Silence can be the generous move.</strong>
          <span>
            Spencer's term — "negative beneficence" — means doing good by holding back. Not
            every wrong statement is a debt you're owed the satisfaction of collecting.
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="n">03</div>
        <div class="t">
          <strong>The loud and the unearned-authority get corrected.</strong>
          <span>
            If someone is steamrolling the room or being treated as an expert they aren't,
            letting it slide harms everyone listening. That's when you speak.
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="flow">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>Negative Beneficence</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Herbert Spencer's concept from 'The Principles of Ethics' on when to correct others
        or say nothing.
      </p>

      <div class="chart">
        <div class="fc-start">An error is spoken</div>
        <div class="fc-arrow"></div>

        <div class="fc-columns">
          <div class="fc-col correct">
            <div class="fc-col-head">Reasons to Correct</div>
            <div class="fc-card">
              <div class="step">Real Harm</div>
              <div class="ask">Will it cause real damage if no one speaks up?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="fc-card">
              <div class="step">Arrogance</div>
              <div class="ask">Is this person full of themselves?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="fc-card">
              <div class="step">Fake Expert</div>
              <div class="ask">Are people treating them as an expert when they shouldn't?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="fc-card">
              <div class="step">Steamroller</div>
              <div class="ask">Do they bulldoze others to win attention?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="fc-col-foot">All → Yes</div>
          </div>

          <div class="fc-col silent">
            <div class="fc-col-head">Reasons to Stay Silent</div>
            <div class="fc-card">
              <div class="step">Too Small</div>
              <div class="ask">Is the mistake too minor to matter?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="fc-card">
              <div class="step">Unfair Hit</div>
              <div class="ask">Would correcting them make them look worse than they deserve?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="fc-card">
              <div class="step">Good Company</div>
              <div class="ask">Are they generally kind and decent?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="fc-card">
              <div class="step">Showing Off</div>
              <div class="ask">Am I mostly doing this to look smart?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="fc-col-foot">All → Yes</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fc-arrow short"></div>
        <div class="fc-weigh">Weigh the two sides against each other</div>
        <div class="fc-arrow"></div>

        <div class="fc-end">
          <div class="fc-result go">
            <div class="rtag">If the left side prevails</div>
            <h4>Correct It</h4>
          </div>
          <div class="fc-result stay">
            <div class="rtag">If the right side prevails</div>
            <h4>Stay Silent</h4>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* Source quote block */
  .source {
    padding: 48px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }
  .source .label {
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--mute);
    margin-bottom: 18px;
  }
  .source blockquote {
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--charcoal);
    max-width: 72ch;
  }
  .source cite {
    display: block;
    margin-top: 18px;
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 500;
    font-style: normal;
    color: var(--ink);
  }

  /* Section rhythm */
  section.tree {
    padding: 48px 0;
  }
  .tree-intro {
    font-size: 32px;
    line-height: 1.2;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .tree-intro + p {
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--mute);
    max-width: 60ch;
    margin-bottom: 48px;
  }

  /* Decision node */
  .node {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
  .q {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    padding: 24px 0;
  }
  .q .step {
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--mute);
  }
  .q h3 {
    font-size: 24px;
    line-height: 1.2;
    font-weight: 500;
    margin: 8px 0 12px;
  }
  .q .plain {
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--charcoal);
    max-width: 64ch;
  }
  .q .original {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--mute);
    max-width: 64ch;
    margin-top: 12px;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  /* Branch pills */
  .branches {
    display: flex;
    gap: 8px;
    margin-top: 18px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
  .pill {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    height: 48px;
    padding: 0 32px;
    border-radius: 30px;
    font-size: 16px;
    font-weight: 500;
    font-family: inherit;
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    cursor: default;
  }
  .pill.yes {
    background: var(--ink);
    color: #fff;
    border-color: var(--ink);
  }
  .pill.no {
    background: var(--soft-cloud);
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .pill small {
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--mute);
    margin-left: 10px;
    font-size: 14px;
  }
  .pill.yes small {
    color: #9e9ea0;
  }

  /* Connector */
  .connector {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 12px;
    padding: 18px 0 6px;
    color: var(--mute);
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
  }
  .connector::before {
    content: '↓';
    font-size: 18px;
  }

  /* Outcomes */
  .outcomes {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 8px;
    margin-top: 48px;
  }
  .outcome {
    padding: 30px;
    background: var(--soft-cloud);
  }
  .outcome.correct {
    background: var(--ink);
    color: #fff;
  }
  .outcome .tag {
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }
  .outcome.correct .tag {
    color: #9e9ea0;
  }
  .outcome.silent .tag {
    color: var(--mute);
  }
  .outcome h4 {
    font-size: 24px;
    line-height: 1.2;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }
  .outcome p {
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
  .outcome.silent p {
    color: var(--charcoal);
  }
  .outcome.correct p {
    color: #e5e5e5;
  }

  /* Social translation */
  .social {
    padding: 48px 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }
  .social h2 {
    font-size: 32px;
    line-height: 1.2;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
  }
  .social .row {
    display: flex;
    gap: 16px;
    padding: 18px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--hairline-soft);
  }
  .social .row .n {
    font-size: 24px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--mute);
    min-width: 48px;
  }
  .social .row .t strong {
    display: block;
    font-size: 16px;
    font-weight: 500;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }
  .social .row .t span {
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--mute);
  }

  /* Flowchart */
  .flow {
    padding: 48px 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }
  .flow h2 {
    font-size: 32px;
    line-height: 1.2;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .flow .lead {
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--mute);
    max-width: 90ch;
    margin-bottom: 48px;
  }
  .chart {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
  }
  .fc-start {
    background: var(--ink);
    color: #fff;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    padding: 14px 32px;
    border-radius: 30px;
    text-align: center;
    max-width: 520px;
  }
  .fc-arrow {
    width: 1px;
    height: 28px;
    background: var(--ink);
    position: relative;
    flex: 0 0 auto;
  }
  .fc-arrow::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 0;
    left: 50%;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    border-left: 5px solid transparent;
    border-right: 5px solid transparent;
    border-top: 7px solid var(--ink);
  }
  .fc-arrow.short {
    height: 18px;
  }

  .fc-columns {
    display: flex;
    gap: 8px;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 840px;
  }
  .fc-col {
    flex: 1;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }
  .fc-col-head {
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 14px 18px;
  }
  .fc-col.correct .fc-col-head {
    background: var(--ink);
    color: #fff;
  }
  .fc-col.silent .fc-col-head {
    background: var(--soft-cloud);
    color: var(--ink);
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }
  .fc-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    border-top: none;
    padding: 18px;
    background: var(--canvas);
  }
  .fc-card .step {
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--mute);
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }
  .fc-card .ask {
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.3;
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .fc-col-foot {
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--mute);
    text-align: center;
    padding: 12px;
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    border-top: none;
  }

  .fc-weigh {
    background: var(--soft-cloud);
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    padding: 14px 32px;
    text-align: center;
    max-width: 560px;
  }
  .fc-end {
    display: flex;
    gap: 8px;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 560px;
  }
  .fc-result {
    flex: 1;
    padding: 24px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .fc-result.go {
    background: var(--ink);
    color: #fff;
  }
  .fc-result.stay {
    background: var(--soft-cloud);
    color: var(--ink);
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }
  .fc-result .rtag {
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }
  .fc-result.go .rtag {
    color: #9e9ea0;
  }
  .fc-result.stay .rtag {
    color: var(--mute);
  }
  .fc-result h4 {
    font-size: 20px;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .tree-intro,
    .social h2,
    .flow h2 {
      font-size: 24px;
    }
    .outcomes {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
    .branches {
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: flex-start;
    }
    .fc-columns {
      flex-direction: column;
    }
    .fc-end {
      flex-direction: column;
    }
  }
</style>
